[[File:Certificate of attendance Wellcome L0069059.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Certificate of attendance (in this case for Richard Colmer, surgeon) at anatomy and surgery courses run by [[William Hunter (anatomist)|William Hunter]]. The certificate is signed by him and dated 27th April 1755 by hand. The upper part of the certificate is an engraving of a bust of [[William Harvey]].]]
A '''certificate of attendance''' (also '''certificate of participation''' or '''certificate of completion''')<ref name=Haylock>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.it/books?id=cjaFCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&dq=%22certificate+of+attendance+is%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwja7OfK0NfOAhWlDcAKHXPsBNMQ6AEIODAD#v=onepage&q=%22certificate%20of%20attendance%20is%22&f=false |title=Supportive Cancer Care |editor1-first=David|editor1-last= Alberts |editor2-first=Maria |editor2-last=Lluria-Prevatt |editor3-first=Stephanie |editor3-last=Kha, |editor4-first=Karen |editor4-last=Weihs |publisher=Springer|year= 2016 |page=24 |ISBN =9783319248141 |chapter= 2.8.1 Navigator Certification |first1= P.J. |last1= Haylock}}</ref> is an official [[document]] proving the attendance of a class, a language course<ref name=Konstantinidis>{{cite book |url =https://books.google.it/books?id=r5K6BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA102&dq=Teilnahmezertifikat&hl=it&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiSm_vInefOAhXLaxQKHYGoD08Q6AEIKzAC#v=onepage&q=Teilnahmezertifikat&f=false|date= 2015 |page=102 | first=Christine |last=Konstantinidis|title= Sprachen lernen - Tolle Tipps und Tricks: Kreative Methoden für Motivation und maximalen Erfolg|language=German |isbn= 9783734779947}}</ref> or a training course.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://dictionary.cambridge.org/it/dizionario/inglese/certificate-of-attendance| title =certificate of attendance | date = | website = Cambridge Dictionary| publisher =| access-date =2016-08-23 | quote = an official document used to prove that you have been to a class or course for special training}}</ref>
Although it could increase the prospects of professional promotion,<ref name=Konstantinidis/> this type of certificate is not a [[credential]] because it does not provide proof of learning,<ref>{{cite book|title=How to evaluate PDP |url=https://books.google.it/books?id=WlyDVARSa8QC&pg=PA101&dq=%22certificates+of+attendance+are%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjx1qOA0tfOAhWhHsAKHYqSCJkQ6AEITDAH#v=onepage&q=%22certificates%20of%20attendance%20are%22&f=false |first1=Amar |last1= Rughani, |first2=Chris |last2=Franklin, |first3=Stephen |last3=Dixon |publisher=Radcliffe Publishing |year=2003 |work= Career development Personal Development Plans for Dentists: The New Approach to Continuing Professional Development | ISBN =9781857759174 }}</ref> that is, no knowledge is assessed before such a certificate is issued.<ref name=Haylock/>
==United States== In the United States and Canada, a '''certificate of attendance''' is a certificate given to students who complete the K-12 ([[kindergarten]] through [[Twelfth grade|12th grade]]) program but do not meet the requirements for the [[high school diploma]] or the modified diploma.
Students who complete 12th grade but did not obtain enough [[Course credit|credits]], did not complete all core courses, did not pass required testing or did not meet the goals outlined in their individualized program will still be acknowledged in the graduation ceremony; they will walk across the stage in cap and gown, and will look like a graduate. Instead of receiving a diploma, however, they will receive a certificate of attendance. Some students are encouraged to return to school for either a full year or more (and then to graduate whenever they finish) to make up their credits, pass required testing or meet their goals, and finally obtain a regular or modified diploma. Some alternative programs allow students to finish in half year provided that they meet certain requirements.
Some schools do not allow these students to participate in the graduation ceremony. This is controversial as some students feel that the social benefits of graduation are important.{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}
===Certification of completion=== Upon completion of a college or university certificate program, students generally receive a '''certification of completion''' or '''certificate of achievement''', not a degree or diploma. Candidates who are enrolled in an institution as full or part-time students may be able to transfer these certificates to degree programs at other institutions.
Students with disabilities who complete the required [[Individualized Education Program ]] but do not meet the requirements of the high school diploma who complete 12th grade may also be awarded a '''certificate of completion'''.
