[[File:MHBgreaser.jpg|thumb|right|North American greaser of [[Quebec]], Canada, ''circa'' 1960]]
'''Greasers''' are a [[youth subculture]] that was popularized in the late 1940s and 1950s to 1960s by predominantly [[working class]] and [[American lower class|lower class]] [[teenager]]s and [[young adult (psychology)|young adults]] in the [[United States]]. The subculture remained prominent into the mid-1960s and was particularly embraced by certain ethnic groups in [[urban areas]], particularly [[Italian-Americans]] and [[Hispanic-American]]s. [[Rock and roll]] music, [[rockabilly]] and [[doo-wop]] were major parts of the culture.

== History ==
=== Etymology of the term "greaser" ===
The word "greaser" originated in the 19th century in the United States as a derogatory label for poor laborers, specifically those of Mexican or Italian descent.{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=138}}{{efn|The similar term “greaseball” became a slur for individuals of [[Italians|Italian]] descent, though to a lesser extent it has also been used more generally to refer to all [[Mediterranean race|Mediterranean]], Latin, or [[Hispanic]] people.<ref name="slang">{{cite book|last1=Dalzell|first1=Tom|last2=Victor|first2=Terry|title=The New Partridge Dictionary of Slang and Unconventional English|date=2015|publisher=Routledge|page=1044|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bbcBCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1044&dq=greaseball&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1pMLHk_rYAhXLzVMKHdu3DJkQ6AEIMjAC#v=onepage&q=greaseball&f=false|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref><ref name="maledicta">{{cite book|last1=Aman|first1=Reinhold|title=Maledicta, Volume 7|date=1984|publisher=Maledicta|page=29|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wAnqAAAAMAAJ&q=greaseball+italian&dq=greaseball+italian&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj79PfqlPrYAhVCtlMKHZCwA-w4ChDoAQg8MAQ}}</ref><ref name="migrations">{{cite book|last1=Ruberto|first1=Laura E.|last2=Sciorra|first2=Joseph|title=New Italian Migrations to the United States: Vol. 1: Politics and History since 1945|date=2017|publisher=University of Illinois Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qauzDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT118&dq=greaseball+italian&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwibrJumlPrYAhWF2lMKHVZPBp8Q6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=greaseball%20italian&f=false}}</ref>}} The term was later used to refer to mechanics. It was not used in writing to refer to the American subculture of the mid-20th century until the mid-1960s, though in this sense it still evoked a pejorative connotation and a relation to machine work.{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=138}}{{efn|[[S. E. Hinton]], author of the novel [[The Outsiders (novel)|''The Outsiders'']], an influential portrayal of greasers, knew the term from her youth in the 1950s.{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=139}}}} The name was applied to members of the subculture because of their characteristic greased-back hair.{{sfn|Torres|2017}}

=== Origins of the subculture and rise to popularity ===
The greaser subculture may have emerged in the post-[[World War II]] era among the [[motorcycle club]]s and [[outlaw motorcycle club|gangs]] of the late 1940s, though it was certainly established by the 1950s.{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=138}}{{efn|Moore writes that there is ambiguity surrounding the birth of the defining greaser fashion and style, though the associated look is similar to the one displayed by post-war bikers.{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=138}}}} The original greasers were aligned by a feeling of disillusion with American popular culture, either through a lack of economic opportunity in spite of the [[Economic history of the United States#Postwar prosperity: 1945–1973|post-war boom]] or a marginalization enacted by the general domestic shift towards homogeneity.{{sfn|Moore|2017|pp=138–139}} Most were male, often ethnic and working-class, and held interest in [[hotrod]] culture or motorcycling.{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=138}} A handful of middle class youth were drawn to the subculture for its rebellious attitude.{{sfn|Symmons|2016|p=182}}

The weak structural foundation of the greasers can be attributed to the subculture's origins in working-class youth with few economic resources with which they could participate in American [[consumerism]].{{sfn|Cinotto|2014|loc=Anticipating an Italian American Consumption Culture}} Greasers, unlike motorcyclists, did not explicitly have their own interest clubs or publications. As such, there was no business marketing geared specifically towards the group.{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=141}} Their choice in clothing was largely drawn from a common understanding of the empowering aesthetic of working-class attire, rather than cohesive association with similarly-dressed individuals.{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=141}} Some greasers were in motorcycle clubs or in gangs (and some gang members and bikers dressed like greasers){{sfn|Moore|2017|p=141}} though such membership was not an inherent principle of the subculture.{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=138}}

Ethnically, original greasers were mostly composed of [[Italian Americans]] in the [[Northeastern United States]] and [[Chicanos]] in the [[Southwestern United States|Southwest]]. Since both of these peoples were mostly [[olive skin|olive-skinned]], the "greaser" label assumed a quasi-racial status that implied an urban lower class masculinity and delinquency. This development led to an ambiguity in the racial distinction between poor [[Italian American]]s and [[Puerto Rican migration to New York City#1950s|Puerto Ricans]] in [[New York City]] in the 1950s and 1960s.{{sfn|Cinotto|2014|loc=Anticipating an Italian American Consumption Culture}} Greasers were also perceived as being predisposed to perpetrating sexual violence, stoking fear among middle class males and a degree of arousal among middle class females.{{sfn|Symmons|2016|pp=181–182}}

=== Decline and modern incarnations ===
Though the television show ''[[American Bandstand]]'' helped to "sanitize" the negative image of greasers in the 1960s, [[Promiscuity|sexual promiscuity]] was still seen as a key component of the modern character.{{sfn|Cinotto|2014|loc=Footnote #56}} By the mid-1970s, the greaser image had become a quintessential part of 1950s nostalgia and cultural revival.{{sfn|Symmons|2016|p=184}}

== Fashion, style, and culture ==
[[File:Young greaser.jpg|thumb|Young greaser in the Southeastern United States, 1956]]
The most notable physical characteristic of greasers were their greased hair styles through the use of products such as [[pomade]] or [[petroleum jelly]]. For males, it was used to fashion coiffures such as the Folsom, [[Pompadour (hairstyle)|Pompadour]], Elephant's trunk, or [[Duck's ass]]. This was probably adopted from early rock 'n' roll and [[rockabilly]]
performers such as [[Elvis Presley]]. Since the hair products weren't sticky and remained wet the hair had to be frequently reshaped via combing so the style could be maintained.{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=139}} For females, [[backcombing]] or teasing the hair was common.{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=140}}

Male greasers typically wore loose cotton twill trousers (common among the working class) or dark blue [[Levi Strauss & Co.|Levi's]] [[blue jeans|jeans]] (widely popular among all American youth in the 1950s). The latter were often cuffed over ankle-high black or brown leather boots,{{sfn|Moore|2017|p=139}} including cowboy, steel-toed [[engineer boot|engineer]], or [[Harness boots|harness]] styles. Other footwear choices included [[Chuck Taylor All-Stars]] and [[brothel creeper]]s.{{sfn|Blanco F.|2015|p=137}} Male tops were typically solid black or white [[T-shirt]]s, [[ringer T-shirt]]s, or sometimes [[tank tops]] (which would have been retailed as underwear). Outerwear were either denim or [[leather jacket]]s (including but not limited to [[Perfecto motorcycle jacket]]s). Female greaser dress included leather jackets and risque clothing such as tight and cropped pants like [[capri pants|capris]] and [[pedal pushers]] (broadly popular during the time period).{{sfn|Moore|2017|pp=139–140}}

=== Music tastes ===
In the early 1950s there was significant greaser interest in [[doo-wop]], a black genre of music from the industrial cities of the Northeast that had disseminated to mainstream American music through Italian American performers.{{sfn|Cinotto|2014|loc=Anticipating an Italian American Consumption Culture}} Greasers were also heavily associated with the culture surrounding [[rock n' roll]], a musical genre which had induced feelings of a [[moral panic]] among older, middle class generations during the mid to late 1950s. To many of them, greasers epitomized the connection between rock music and juvenile delinquency professed by several important social and cultural observers at the time.{{sfn|Symmons|2016|pp=181–182}}

== Portrayal in media and popular culture ==
[[File:LA teens.jpg|thumb|Greaser revival look in 1974]]
The first cinematic representation of the greaser subculture was the 1953 film ''[[The Wild One]]''.{{sfn|Gelder|Thornton|1997|p=185}}

Greasers are central characters in the 1957 musical ''[[West Side Story]]'' and its 1961 [[West Side Story (film)|film adaptation]], the 1967 novel ''[[The Outsiders (novel)|The Outsiders]]'' and its 1983 [[The Outsiders (film)|film adaptation]], the 1974 film ''[[The Lords of Flatbush]]'', and the 1979 film ''[[The Wanderers (1979 film)|The Wanderers]]''. The phenomenon was given a more farcical treatment in the 1971 stage musical ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]'' (along with its 1978 [[Grease (film)|film adaptation]]), which drew its name from the subculture and was based on real-life [[Poles in Chicago|Chicago Polish]] greasers in the late 1950s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bring back our own, original R-rated 'Grease'|url=http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/the_theater_loop/2009/01/bring-back-our.html|accessdate=28 June 2015|date=8 January 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131117163229/http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/the_theater_loop/2009/01/bring-back-our.html|archivedate=17 November 2013}}</ref>

The band [[Sha-Na-Na]] models their on-stage presence on New York City greasers (the band members themselves were mostly [[Ivy League]]rs).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/danny-mcbride-guitarist-with-rockn-roll-revivalists-sha-na-na-1773502.html?action=Popup|date=April 10, 2010|publisher=''[[The Independent]]''|title=Danny McBride: Guitarist with rock'n' roll revivalists Sha Na Na}}</ref>

