{{Infobox album | name = Ode to the Death of Jazz | type = Album | artist = [[Edward Vesala]] | cover = Ode to the Death of Jazz.jpg | alt = | released = 1990 | recorded = April and May 1989 | venue = | studio = | genre = [[Jazz]] | length = 55:55 | label = [[ECM Records|ECM]] | producer = [[Manfred Eicher]] | chronology = [[Edward Vesala]] | prev_title = [[Lumi (album)|Lumi]] | prev_year = 1986 | next_title = [[Invisible Storm]] | next_year = 1991 }}
'''''Ode to the Death of Jazz''''' is an album by Finnish avant-garde jazz composer, bandleader and drummer [[Edward Vesala]] recorded in 1989 and released on the [[ECM Records|ECM]] label in 1990.<ref name="ECM discography">[http://www.ecmrecords.com/Catalogue/ECM/1400/1413.php ECM discography] accessed October 4, 2011</ref>
==Reception== The [[Allmusic]] review by Brian Olewnick awarded the album 2½ stars stating "it feels as though something essential is being restrained, as though Vesala is reluctant to simply let his ensemble surge forward unbound. Fine instrumental work abounds, however, notably by the leader himself on drums and the Garbarek-laden tones of tenor saxophonist Jouni Kannisto. In sum, the listener gets the impression that, although all the elements are in place for a fine album, excessive control has led to a dilution of the power that could have been".<ref name="Allmusic">Olewnick, B. [http://www.allmusic.com/album/ode-to-the-death-of-jazz-r149524/review Allmusic Review] accessed October 4, 2011</ref> {{Album ratings | rev1 = ''[[Allmusic]]'' | rev1Score = {{rating|2.5|5}}<ref name="Allmusic"/>}}
==Track listing== :''All compositions by Edward Vesala'' # "Sylvan Swizzle" - 8:34 # "Infinite Express" - 7:54 # "Time to Think" - 7:34 # "Winds of Sahara" - 4:19 # "Watching for the Signal" - 8:13 # "A Glimmer of Sepal" - 5:26 # "Mop Mop" - 5:37 # "What? Where? Hum Hum" - 8:19 :*Recorded at Sound and Fury Studio in Helsinki, Finland in April and May 1989
