[[Image:Paragraphos.png|thumb|Various paragraphoi.]]
A '''paragraphos''' ({{lang-grc|{{linktext|παράγραφος}}}}, ''parágraphos'', from ''para-'', “beside”, and ''graphein'', “to write”) was a mark in [[ancient Greek|ancient]] [[Greek punctuation]], marking a division in a text (as between speakers in a dialogue or drama) or drawing the reader's attention to another division mark, such as the [[two dot punctuation]] mark {{angle bracket|<big><big>[[⁚]]</big></big>}}. There are many variants of this symbol, sometimes supposed to have developed from Greek [[gamma]] ({{lang|grc|Γ}}), the first letter of the word ''graphos''. It was usually placed at the beginning of a line and trailing a little way under or over the text.<ref name=chasejoy>Pearse, Roger. "[http://www.roger-pearse.com/weblog/2010/11/09/paragraphos-and-coronis-the-joy-of-the-chase/ Paragraphos and Coronis—the joy of the chase]". 9 Nov 2010. Accessed 9 Oct 2014.</ref>
It was referenced by [[Aristotle]], who was dismissive of its use.<ref name=moreon>Pearse, Roger. "[http://www.roger-pearse.com/weblog/2010/11/10/more-on-the-paragraphos-mark/ More on the paragraphos mark]". 10 Nov 2010. Accessed 9 Oct 2014.</ref>
[[Unicode]] encodes multiple versions: *{{unichar|2e0f|Paragraphos|html=}} *{{unichar|2e10|Forked Paragraphos|html=}} *{{unichar|2e11|Reversed Forked Paragraphos|html=}}
